BHP, CSL, Goodman, Qantas, Woodside: Australian Stock Preview

-- B y   S h a n i   R a j a
-- 
2011-06-29T22:57:31Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-06-29/bhp-csl-goodman-macquarie-qantas-woodside-australian-stock-preview.html
The following is a list of companies
whose shares may have unusual moves in  Australia . The preview
includes news announced after markets closed. All prices are
from yesterday’s close unless otherwise stated.  The S&P/ASX 200 Index futures contract due in September
rose 0.7 percent to 4,550 as of 6:59 a.m. in Sydney. The Bank of
 New York  Australia ADR Index gained 1.7 percent. The S&P/ASX 200
Index advanced 1.2 percent to 4,529.50.  Mining companies: Copper futures for September delivery
rose 2.8 percent in New York after reports that more Americans
than forecast signed contracts to buy previously owned homes and
Japanese industrial production expanded.  BHP Billiton Ltd. (BHP)  , the world’s No. 1 mining
company, advanced 1.8 percent to A$43.15. Its American
depositary receipts gained 1.6 percent in New York trading.  Rio Tinto Group (RIO AU), the world’s second-largest mining
company by sales, climbed 1.5 percent to A$81.53 in Sydney.  Oil stocks: Oil rose for a third day, after climbing 2
percent yesterday in New York.  Woodside Petroleum Ltd. (WPL)  , Australia’s second-
biggest oil and gas producer, rose 2.5 percent to A$40.62.
 Santos Ltd. (STO)  , Australia’s third-largest oil and gas
producer, rallied 2.2 percent to A$13.20.  Gold producers: Gold futures for August delivery rose 0.7
percent in New York.  Newcrest Mining Ltd. (NCM)  , Australia
biggest gold producer, climbed 2.1 percent to A$37.10.        CSL Ltd. (CSL)  : The drugmaker was raised to “neutral”
from “underperform” at Macquarie Group Ltd. The stock advanced
2.4 percent to A$32.30.        Goodman Group (GMG)  Ltd: The Australian investment
trust agreed to sell a 50 percent stake in the Hong Kong
Interlink Project to Canada Pension Plan Investment Board for
about A$274 million. The stock dropped 0.7 percent to 70
Australian cents.        Qantas Airways Ltd. (QAN)  : Australia’s biggest carrier
extended cancellations of New Zealand services after a volcanic
ash cloud that has disrupted flights for three weeks continued
to hover over the smaller country. Qantas shares were unchanged
at A$1.815.        Macquarie Group Ltd. (MQG)  : Australia’s biggest
investment bank was downgraded to “hold” from “buy” at
Deutsche Bank AG. Its shares gained 0.4 percent to A$30.81.  To contact the reporter on this story:
Shani Raja in Sydney at 
 sraja4@bloomberg.net .  To contact the editors responsible for this story:
Nick Gentle at 
 ngentle2@bloomberg.net . 